@node Introduction "Introduction"

  Introduction

    RefLandscape allows you to generate fractal landscapes with
    Reflections 4. It will create a Chess-Object and modify it's
    height levels.

@endnode

@node Copyright "Copyright and Distribution"

  Copyright and Distribution

    This package is freeware. So use it, spreed it .. improve it (;-

@endnode

@node Requirements "What you need"

  What you need

    Of course Reflections V4.

    Created landscapes can become very big.
    For the moment until 65536 points.
    So enough memory will be needed.

@endnode

@node Installation "Installation"

  Installation

    Simple copy both files out of the Generator directory in
    this package, to the place you believe to put it.

    If you put the landscape programm in an other directory
    than the landscape.rexx, simple change the "LandScapePath"
    constant in the script to the right path.

    Thats all.

@endnode

@node RefLandscape  "RefLandscape"

  RefLandscape

    This tool is devided in two parts. That for the
    following reason :

      I don't know how to make external programs
      running with reflections.
      Cause the documentation is not available yet.

    But I will know it very soon.

    @{"Landscape" link Landscape} is a simple programm that
    generates a fractal landscape and prints out a list of
    the height levels.

    @{"Landscape.rexx" link Landscape.rexx} will generate a Chess-Object
    and modify it's height levels as described by landscape.

    So all you need to do is starting Reflections and
    then the landscape ARexx module.

@endnode

@node Landscape  "Landscape"

  Landscape

    Is a command line interface only programm to
    produce a list of height levels on the standart
    output, those are calculated with a simple
    landscape fractal algorithm.

    It's arguments :

    L=HELP/S,S=STEPS/K/N,H=HEIGHT/K/N,R=RANDOM/K/N

    Help   : Prints out some useless help.
    Steps  : Number of iterations to go from 1 up to 8 for the moment.
             The final landscape will have a size of steps^2 * steps^2.
             That means for example : steps = 3 => a grid of 8x8.
    Height : The maximum height of the landscape. 20 will mean
             that the lowest point is -20 and the highest +20.
    Random : The initial random seed. The most essential thing.
             Same seed equals to a same landscape

    The result is a file with header and other informations and
    a list with the height levels. To save it in a file simple
    redirect it to one.

    Example of usage :

        landscape h=30 > test

    Will make a file "test" with the result list. And a maximum
    height of 30 will be used.

    NOTICE : If you don't pass any argument the following values
             will be used -> S=5 H=10 R=100

@endnode

@node Landscape.rexx  "Landscape.rexx"

  Landscape.rexx

    This little ARexx script is provided to make the link
    between landscape and Reflections. Cause landscape is,
    for the moment, not made as external module for Reflections.

    This means that the processing will slow down. Very down, don't
    try to generate an 8 step iterated fractal if you want to work
    on your Computer during the rest of the day (:-)
    ARexx scripts are not made to process thousands of datas and so on.

    You can start it in a shell with "rx landscape.rexx"
    or use it as internal ARexx module in Reflections.

    You will be requested to enter some informations like :

     - The name of the object you want to create.
     - The number of iterations to calculate 1..8.
     - The initial seed of the fractal.
     - The maximum height of the fractal.

    Sorry, but I did'nt implement some tests if you
    press "annulate" instead of "ok".

    All steps, while the processing, will be documented
    in the footer line.

    This script creates a temporary file, for the height levels,
    so be carfull if you already have files with the name
    "MatrixFile". The script tests if there already exists
    a file with a name like this, AND offers you the
    option to delete it. Usefull after a crash. A crash ? ...

@endnode

